<H3>Ground Pickup</H3>
<p>
Used an array of 360 degrees of elevation and 180 degrees of azimuth. Took 
each profile over this array, with center offset from el=90 by the zenith angle
(<i>za</i>). Used numpy.roll to shift the beam center relative to the array - 
this works because elevation ranges from 
-180 to 180. For instance if za=270 (level with horizon and "behind" you), 
roll() will move the lower half of the beam corresponding to el<-180 up to the 
top of the array where el>0:
<p>
<b>Baffled beam through a range of zenith angles</b>
<table border="1">
<tr><th>za=60
<th>za=120
<th>za=180
<th>za=240
<th>za=300
<th>za=0
<tr>
<td><a href="roll_60.png"><img src="roll_60.png" width=300></a>
<td><a href="roll_120.png"><img src="roll_120.png" width=300></a>
<td><a href="roll_180.png"><img src="roll_180.png" width=300></a>
<td><a href="roll_240.png"><img src="roll_240.png" width=300></a>
<td><a href="roll_300.png"><img src="roll_300.png" width=300></a>
<td><a href="roll_0.png"><img src="roll_0.png" width=300></a>
</table>
<p>
For each za, sum the elements of the pattern array which correspond to el<=0, 
and divide by the sum of the entire array. Results of each sum plotted against 
za: 
<p>
<a href="pickup_comparison.png">
<img src="pickup_comparison.png" width=1300></a>
<hr>
<H3>Intensity Spectra</H3>
Multiplied the ground pickup at each zenith angle by the Planck intensity 
function for a 290K blackbody. Called <i>am</i> at each za - notice the 
saturation at ozone lines near 60 and 120 GHz, where increased airmass has no 
effect on  intensity. Without the baffle, there is <20dB difference between the 
atmospheric and ground spectra for every zenith angle. With the baffle, there is
>20dB difference up to za=50. 
<p>
<table><tr><th>Without baffle<th>With baffle<tr><td>
<a href="i_spec_nobaff.png">
<img src="i_spec_nobaff.png" width=800></a>
<td><a href="i_spec_baff.png">
<img src="i_spec_baff.png" width=800></a>
</table>
